5 Tips for Visiting📍Grutas Tolatongo Hot Springs

1. Plan to visit on a week day if possible, to avoid crowds. The place is massive though, so even on a busy day, you can find privacy.

2. Bring waterproof sandals (not flip flops) or water shoes to walk around in the hot spring river.

3. Rent a car or take a tour, as the drive is about 8 hours round trip from Mexico City (BUT WORTH IT!). We booked an experience through @tripadvisor, which allowed us to sit back and relax throughout the journey - plus, we met some other cool people doing it that way.

4. Take the zip line down! You ride 4 different tracks over the cactus-lined mountains and Gatorade-blue river. Can’t be missed, and more fun than walking.

5. Don’t bring your own lunch - there are a ton of authentic, local restaurants in the area to check out and their margaritas are 🤌🏼

If you’re planning a trip any time before the new year, or even if you’re sticking around home, use the code JASMINE10 to receive 10% off of an experience booked through TripAdvisor :) (also a great holiday gift idea… just sayin’)

#travel #travelwithtripadvisor #travelgram #travelblogger #mexico #tolantongo #grutasdetolantongo #canadiantraveller #traveltips

2 DAY HUNTINGTON BEACH ITINERARY

I had no idea that you could fly direct from Vancouver or Victoria to Orange County, but this was probably the quickest weekend trip I’ve ever done. And I’ll do it again, I tell ya!

Here are some of the recommendations I have from our visit to @surfcityusa, but I’m excited to get back down here again the next time I’m feeling the seasonal effectiveness disorder kick in, so please send your own suggestions my way!

Stay:
* @paseahotel: it’s affordable, cozy, and located right across from the beach but within walking distance to all of the spots we visited throughout our trip (they also have their own ice rink up-and-running until mid January)

Eat:
* @tannershb (chilaquiles or avocado toast with ricotta), @sessionswestcoastdeli (best cold brew lattes) *for breakfast/brunch
* @ola_mexican_kitchen (taquitos, tacos, micheladas, everything), @simmzys (tortilla soup or brussel sprouts), @dukeshb (surf & turf or scallops) *for lunch/dinner

Drink:
* @thebungalowhb (great service and you feel like you’re in your grandmas house but better)
* @treehousehb (a cute rooftop bar with an ocean view)
* Pier Summit Lodge retro ski pop-up in @shorebreakresort (seasonal)

Do:
* Skate at @paseahotel (seasonal)
* Roller skate (rent from @surfcityskates) or rent bikes (@paseahotel offers them for free to guests) for a sunset rip on the paved beach path
* Visit the Bosa Chica Ecological Reserve to see a number of cool birds and escape to nature within the city
* Take surf lessons with @corkycarrollsurfschool
* Do all-levels community beach yoga by donation with @yogaonthebeachhuntingtonbeach

*save for future reference!*

#surfcityusa

I tried to put as many Canadian-made things in my place as I could - from the bedding, to the furniture, to some odds and ends from small, local businesses. A few of my favourite pieces though, are my couch, matching bed frame, and this cool little mcm-style coffee table. They all come from a company based out of Saskatchewan called @pivotsubscriptions, where their furniture is also manufactured.

The quality is amazing, it’s super comfy, and fits pretty perfectly with my style of decor. But the really interesting thing about this company is that they offer a subscription option, so you can pay monthly and switch up your space when you feel like it! It’s all part of a circular and sustainable approach to furniture shopping, and I think it’s great that it’s becoming more available throughout Canada.

You know, the last thing I expected was that living my life on the internet would somehow translate into a full-time job. It still kind of blows my mind. Admittedly, I don’t like to talk about the “business” side of things much, as I’ve always tried to keep that stuff separate. I used social media as a diary of my experiences and life events long before there was an opportunity to work with brands or build your own. Though at the same time, I think we all realize that marketing, building a business, and promoting ideas through social media is fairly commonplace at this point. I see it as a great opportunity for women in particular to find financial independence and have a larger voice. I also see it as a way to celebrate a growing industry where WOMEN are the top earners - how often does that happen???

The other day I had the opportunity to speak to a group of young women as part of a #BrighterConnections workshop for @shaw x @minervabc. Minerva BC is a nonprofit organization aimed at providing support to self-identifying women and girls in business and leadership. It was really rewarding to be able to share my experiences in entrepreneurship but even more rewarding to see that there are programs out there that exist for women who want to find mentorship and resources for success.
 I’ll share more about it soon, but in the meantime, if you’re interested in any of the programs that Minerva BC has to offer, you can visit the link in my profile :)

If I ever own a bar in my future, you can expect something similar. A must-hang. @mountpleasantvintage

I was nervous as heck, but honoured that I’d be asked to take part in the @minervabc x @shaw #BrighterConnections workshop, where a few of us had the opportunity to speak with a small group of young women about our own personal experiences in business and entrepreneurship.

For me, a big lesson over the last few years when it comes to my work, has been learning to get comfortable in advocating for my value. Like many women, I’ve struggled with the internal notion that I don’t deserve to be where I am, that asking for more means being greedy, or that being assertive means I’m being a b*tch. That is false for all of us, but it’s a common insecurity in women who find some measure of success. Unfortunately this belief, whether subconscious or unconscious, can impede our progress and keep us from reaching our true potential. Knowing this was (and is) a challenge for me, I thought it would be a great thing to discuss.

Minerva BC is a nonprofit organization dedicated to helping young women own their success by providing access to resources, mentorship and community. Something that is so important for all generations of women coming up in the workforce.

If you’d like to learn more about the programs that @minervabc offers, I’ve put a link in my bio :)

HUGE NEWS 🎉 British Columbia just made birth control free, starting on April 1st! It's a huge win for reproductive rights and access to healthcare, and it's been a long time coming. Did you know that birth control wasn't even legal in Canada until 1969? And even then, it was only available to married women with their husband's consent. It took decades of activism and advocacy from brave women (and men) to expand access to contraception, fight for our bodily autonomy, and break down barriers to healthcare. To all those who fought for this progress, thank you.

While for decades we had been paying for birth control pills that messed with our hormones and $500 to be put through the inhumane torture of getting an IUD, the quick, reversible (with a 90-95% success rate), minimally invasive, and pain-managed vasectomy has been free for years… ain’t that a shocker.  I’m happy that it’s finally happening and hoping that it quickly expands to other provinces, but at the same time it makes me even more saddened by the fact that things related to reproductive rights continue to regress for our neighbours to the south; just this week there’s been more discussions about banning abortion pills (the only access remaining for some) across the US.

I’m feeling as many mixed emotions as I felt with this friggin bird, but right now I want us to celebrate this win. Proud to be Canadian, grateful to be living in this province, and the only other thing I can say is “it’s about time”!

My mom sent me a bunch of photos the other day and they had me reminiscing about my childhood, where I grew up, and how much has changed. It’s bittersweet. I am proud of how far I've come, but there will always be that longing for home. 

We didn’t grow up with much but we had everything we needed as kids (and even a homemade skating rink on the septic field one year!). I loved skating and I remember how hard my mom worked to give me the opportunity to do it. She'd drive me to my early morning lessons, pick me up in the evenings, and even made me this dress. We had to take part in a sports financing program in order to subsidize the cost, and though I recall knowing how important that was at the time, I didn’t realize until becoming an adult, just how helpful it was to have access to those types of resources. It allowed me do what I loved all the way through high school.

When it came time to put down the skates and pick a career path though, I didn’t have a ton of guidance. I come from a small town, where I was only exposed to the standard jobs: teacher, nurse, accountant, the various trades (which I believed were mostly designated for men), etc. I made a "risky" choice to go to art & design school but dropped out before I got there. At 17 years old, I had no idea how I could turn something like that into a job and I knew that I needed to be able to support myself. I went a more practical route by becoming a hairstylist and thankfully really loved it - but it does make me wonder what I might have done, had I been given the same access to leadership and career-building resources, that I had been so easily provided in terms of sports funding.

I’ve spoken a few times about @minervabc and the #BrighterConnections event that I was involved in recently through @shaw, which had me thinking a lot about this. Minerva BC is basically what has been missing. It’s a nonprofit that offers guidance, education, support, and mentorship for self-identifying women and girls, so they can feel inspired to succeed. They show young women what is possible, while offering the chance to be introduced to new opportunities.

Learn more about Minerva BC at the link in my bio :)

I’ve always leaned pretty heavily on travelling and leaving home as an escape from the pressures of life. The last handful of years has been a series of cycles, oscillating between periods of obsessive work and intense hyper-focus, into periods of serenity, joy, curiosity and adventure. I have slowly been finding a balance though, which was mostly brought on by the fact that I was forced to stay put throughout 2020. I’ve been learning to value these little moments here at home just as much as the ones I spend exploring other places.

Tomorrow though, I’ll be spending the entire day in transit, as I head down to Central America for the first time in 9 years! I am just as excited as I’ve ever been to travel. I’ll be landing in Costa Rica before heading north, and though I won’t be in Costa Rica for very long, I’m hoping their “Pura Vida” lifestyle might still rub off on me🤞It’s located within the Blue Zone which means that the people there live longer and healthier lives, and this is probably why.

@visit_costarica wants to know how you find reprieve from the pressures of every day life. Do you read? Cook? Hike? Meditate? What brings you calm? Let them know by tagging #tico10 and @visit_costarica in your post. As an easy hack, you can use my template (click on my Reel and tap the “use template” button in the bottom left of the screen), then add your own photos or videos to share what brings you peace and happiness. Those selected will receive a package full of goodies to promote and encourage self-care :)

Celebrating a Nicaraguan sunset in the only way a couple Canadian gals can. #celinedion 

📍@ranchosantana_nicaragua

I met Jose while visiting in Nicaragua. After flying into Costa Rica, he gave me a ride to the border, where I had a chance to spend a few hours with him, chatting about life, various fruits, and learning about his circumstances and goals. Though extremely positive about everything, I could tell that it’s hard to have to live in Costa Rica in order to make enough money for their families back in Nicaragua. Edwin, an equally lovely person who drove me back to the airport, is in a similar situation to José (many Nicaraguans are). He said the hope is to one day buy their own vehicles so they can have their own businesses and live closer to their families. For them, it may be a far-fetched goal but I want to try to make this happen.

Any donations, big or small, would be hugely appreciated! We have the potential to change lives and I believe we can do it!

Link in bio 🤍

One week at @ranchosantana_nicaragua, to be precise. Even after 7 days, I didn’t feel like I fully had the chance to see everything. The resort sits on 2700 acres, with 5 beaches and 4 restaurants where everything from meats, to cheeses, to vegetables come from the property itself.

We enjoyed copious amounts of maracuya, sprinklings of Tajin on everything, got our daily hydration from coconut water, had massages in treehouses, surfed, gave ourselves some sunburns (by ourselves I mean me only), accidentally ate aloe (never do this), had some good laughs, had some good cries, and danced in the sunset while chowing down on the coconuts that we smashed open like psychopaths.

I can honestly never have a bad time with my Tajin Treasure, @alimarieparker, but it was extra fun to have been able to roam around this place together. Girls trips 4 ever!

If you need a new experience and a relaxing getaway with good food, good drinks, and the perfect balance of adventure, @ranchosantana_nicaragua has an amazing deal on from now until the end of summer. Book 4 nights or more and receive 25% off, using code JASMI5 🌴

UPDATE! 🎉 José and Edwin’s message to you!

They figured it out in advance that we were trying to raise the money (I couldn’t find them on IG fast enough to block them from seeing my stories!) but they had no idea how much we managed to accumulate in such a short time. You guys should be so proud of yourselves for this. The impact you’ve made will give Edwin and José, two lovely humans who just needed a boost, a chance to start their own business, live closer to their families and ultimately give them a head start towards a better life.

Of course there are tons of other places that you could have put your money, so I appreciate everyone who contributed, no matter the size of the donation. I love the idea of coming together to alter the trajectory for folks who never would have asked for it in the first place.

Though the $6,600 won’t cover the cost of the whole vehicle, it’s a step in the right direction towards a solid down payment, which will help to make this dream attainable for them. The GoFundMe is still open for those who wish to keep the train rolling :) Link in bio.

Like most millennials, I wasn’t sure if I’d ever be able to buy a home. Even though this almost barely constitutes as one (it’s just a wee guy!), my REALTOR® helped me find all the key features that I was hoping for - far beyond what I would have ever expected for my first place!

First of all, it’s in Whistler. I’d been talking about wanting to move back ever since I left in 2018, and though I’m mostly renting it out for now, it’s still a *pinch me* moment every time I think about that. It’s steps from the gondola, a short walk to three beautiful lakes, and in the heart of what my REALTOR® and I both consider to be an underrated neighbourhood - one that is set to see a lot of growth in the coming years. Not only does that give me peace of mind in terms of my investment, but it makes me feel excited that I get to be a part of it :)

Though I had visions of buying at a lower price point and renovating, my REALTOR® let me know that this would likely take longer, and cost more than I was ready for, due to supply chain and labour shortages. He helped me rationalize my decision by breaking down costs and saving me money in the long run. Instead of something that needed a ton of work, we found a cute, newly renovated space that I could spend more time styling, decorating, and making my own through cosmetic changes.

I still haven’t had a ton of time to let it sink in, but I’m as excited as ever to call myself a homeowner!

If you’re thinking of buying, selling, or you’re looking for someone to match you with your future dream home, you can find your perfect REALTOR® by visiting @realtordotca.

6 tips for visiting Bella Coola:

- Prepare for a journey. It’s a 14-16 hour trip north of Vancouver, with a 43km descent into the valley by a narrow road with hairpin turns, no guard rails, and super steep grades of up to 18% (the steepest highway in Canada). Gear down and give your breaks some time to cool, partway through. You can also take a ferry from Port Hardy.

- Check out some grizzlies. This area of BC is known for having one of the highest concentrations of grizzlies in the world. This comes with its own set of challenges due to the close proximity to the human population and a higher risk of interaction, which may lead to more bears being killed as a result. Be extra mindful of keeping food locked up and trash properly disposed of. I’d suggest a river tour during spawning season, which allow you to watch the bears feasting on salmon as you float on by :)

- Support the indigenous community. Bella Coola is the ancestral home of the Nuxalk People, and there are plenty of ways to support the community. The Nuxalk People are known for their craftsmanship, which can be seen in their totem poles, masks, and other traditional artwork; some of which have been preserved and are on display at Copper Sun Gallery, along with newer pieces from local artists. Petroglyph tours are also organized by this indigenous-owned business.

- Go fishing. This is the perfect place to catch yourself some salmon, halibut, or trout (not in the river with the bears). You can book guided trips or go on your own, keeping in mind that you will need a fishing license and have knowledge about catch limits, etc.

- Go hiking or rock climbing. Bella Coola has a ton of hiking trails, ranging in difficulty, from easy to more challenging backcountry hikes. Popular trails include the Odegaard Falls Trail, Clayton Falls, and the Nuxalk-Carrier Grease Trail, an ancient Indigenous trade route.

- Book your accommodations early. There isn’t a ton of accommodation available, so it’s best to get on it now!

Let me know if you need any specific recommendations! 

#explorebc #bellacoola #britishcolumbia #explorecanada

A cube side table/magazine rack by the iconic furniture designer, Kai Kristiansen for Aksel Kjersgaard, circa 1960. Made in Denmark of Brazilian rosewood and suede. A full-on MCM dream… 😍

Kai Kristiansen is an iconic symbol of the mid-century modern movement and is widely considered one of the most talented designers of the time. Aksel Tjersgaard was known for his teak and rosewood framed mirrors, minimalist dressers, sideboards, and cabinets. Both had a major hand in popularizing Scandinavian modernism, which makes this collaboration pretty cool.

In terms of the material used here, that’s another story: due to heavy restrictions and a trade ban placed on this species of rosewood in 1992, it has become extremely rare to come across and highly sought after. It is usually pretty easy to identify if you compare images online, but what sets it apart is the unique grain pattern, reddish-hue, black streaks, durability and scent (Indian rosewood can smell rose-like also, but its colour is slightly different and pore density is about 2x that of Brazilian rosewood). It is more valuable than teak when comparing MCM furniture, so make sure you tell your parents and/or grandparents to hang onto it if they have any!

Last night I talked in my stories a bit about where I’ve been at lately. The common emotion that I experience at times like this is “guilt”. A lot of that comes from feeling misunderstood and unable to properly explain what’s happening for me, so the value in having people reach out to say “I understand you” is something that I can’t even put into words. Thank you.

To put it as briefly as possible, I struggle a fair bit with time management and prioritizing important tasks, which creates a domino affect in most areas of my life. This spans from how much time I invest into my relationships, how reliable I am for friends, whether or not I answer texts/calls, how long it takes me to respond to emails, how well I take care of myself (physically & mentally), whether or not I eat/what I choose to eat when I do, how little sleep I get, etc. It’s usually pretty constant but I can often keep it under control enough to function and mask these symptoms for others. Sometimes though, it feels like it piles up to the point where I become so overwhelmed that I start questioning why I deserve anything. I feel so much shame, so deeply, that I wonder how anyone else can stand it. While all I want to do is shut down, I am still being depended on to complete projects on time, be there for other people, and attempt to be there for myself, which is always the very last priority. I don’t get days off. They don’t exist. And a lot of the people I do work for don’t seem to think that they should.

Trying to explain it can be so frustrating because it’s nearly impossible to convey the intensity of it. But having received your messages last night has made me feel seen and understood in a way that I normally do not.

I’m obviously so lucky to have access to a community of people who I can reach out to like this, but not everyone does. That’s why I wanted to share this as a post. If it can give at least one person a tiny fraction of the relief it gave me by reading through the comments and seeing how many people DO GET YOU, I will be happy for that.

They say Canadians are nice, but have you ever met the folks from Savannah, Georgia? 🍑 Here are a few facts about the city that you may not know:

1. It’s a small city of only 145,000 and not a single skyscraper in sight!

2. It’s progressive and diverse, with a large LGBTQ+ community and annual #pride festival.

3. The people of Savannah are well known for their southern charm and hospitality. I experienced this virtually everywhere I went and was consistently in such a positive mood because of it.

4. Savannah is home to one of the largest art and design colleges in the US (SCAD), making it a young and vibrant city for music, arts and culture.

5. It is super walkable. This is because Savannah was America’s first planned city, designed in a grid with wide open streets intertwined with shady public squares and parks (and lots of spanish moss).

6. Savannah has a reputation for being one of the most haunted cities in America. Ghost tours and haunted mansions galore.

7. It’s home to one of the top-rated hotels in the US amongst travellers (@perrylanehotel) according to TripAdvisor. # 1 overall in the US and within the top 1% globally. My experience aligns with that.

8. As a coastal city, it has a ton of amazing seafood and  is of course known for its traditional southern cuisine as well as strong contemporary food scene.

9. It’s a popular destination for bachelorette parties and is 100% where I’ll be going if I ever have one of those. You’re all invited.

Big thanks to @tripadvisor for giving me the experience of visiting Georgia for the first time :)

Ah, behold the echo chamber of antiquated norms, where the personal choice of not bearing children equates to a societal crime, apparently. Well, let’s sprinkle in some facts for the uninitiated:

It’s 2023, not the 1950s. Women have consistently been breaking barriers; reaching new heights in every field imaginable, basically sculpting modern society as we know it. And guess what? Many of them did it without having children.

Also, it’s quite amusing that there’s this one-sided narrative focusing solely on women. Quick stat check: according to the U.S. Census Bureau and Canadian statistical data, around 50% of men in their early 30s are childless, yet I hardly see them getting grilled for it. Why is my partner not sharing the limelight of this scrutiny? Or is it just easier to assume I don’t have one?

I’m genuinely curious - can anyone point me to the hordes of keyboard warriors attacking men for being childfree? I’ll wait.

So here’s my resolve, not that I owe it to anyone: I might welcome kids into my life someday, but for now, I choose to live a life unbound by traditional expectations. And yes, I will continue to advocate for the freedom to choose, without judgment.

Brace yourself, world. More child-free content is coming your way.

Oh looky here, it’s a woman without kids… AND she has cats… AND she has a partner?! How could it be??? 😱

Someone wrote this comment on my post about not having kids at age 35, and it sums things pretty perfectly, so I’ll just put it here: 

“I opened up the comment section and immediately saw men commenting on how you ‘must dislike children’, or be ‘jealous of people with children’ or ‘you must actually be miserable inside’ .....it's beyond ridiculous. If a woman chooses not to have children, that is her right. What about the men who choose not to have any? The response then turns to ‘oh you don't want kids? Hell yeah, good for you man.. Go make your money, you don't have to settle.’ I have legitimately heard that entire conversation. Stop attacking women for choosing their happiness over what society deems appropriate. Ladies, that goes for you too.”

To be honest, I didn’t even realize how intense this expectation was until I posted about not having kids. Just the fact that I even STATED it was enough to set people off. Some people even asked me “why I’d feel the need to specify” as if it was some sort of affront to them. But… it’s true… that is my situation… why can I not freely share that?

Eric and I will probably have kids one day. But we agreed long ago that we wanted to a) travel more together and b) work on ourselves to make sure our relationship is in the best place possible before bringing a kid into the world, knowing there will be very little time for spending time on that once a baby comes along.

To any of the women who felt triggered by some of those comments in that post, I’m sorry. Those people are lunatics. You have nothing to question.

To any parents who may have felt like I was comparing my life to theirs, as if mine is somehow better, that is also not it. I’m simply acknowledging and embracing the freedom that I have right now, knowing it will not be forever. 

Tbh, going viral is my nightmare. It drags all of the worst people into what I consider to be a very safe and harmonious community. But I’m hoping we snagged a few good ones out of it too 🥰 

#childfree #millennial #relationship

The Tsūtenkaku Tower is an iconic landmark in Osaka, Japan. It was built in 1912 but experienced damage from a fire and was neglected along with the entire Shinsekai neighbourhood after WWll. It was rebuilt in 1956 and is now registered as a “tangible cultural property”, due to its historic significance. 

Normally the tower is lit up in different colours depending on the season/occasion, but it’s been undergoing maintenance and hasn’t been lit up for a couple of years (that first photo is a little photoshop trickery to give you an idea). Typically the lights on the very top of the tower would signal the weather forecast for the next day too - white for sunny, blue for rainy, orange for cloudy. If only Eric knew that the following day, it’d be raining on his proposal 😅

Even though we didn’t get the full lit-up view, I thought the tower and the whole neighbourhood of Shinsekai was pretty darn cool! Would highly recommend checking it out.

I’ve hardly left my house since I got back from my trip so this makes my last few weeks look more densely exciting than it actually was. However, it WAS a genuinely exciting experience to try out A&W’s new One Cup program (and visit the new Brew Bar for the first time)!

‘One Cup’ is not your average reusable cup - think of it more as an “exchangeable” cup. It has a leak-proof, resealable lid, can be used for hot and cold beverages, and costs $3. But rather than taking it home, washing it, and trying to remember to take it with you next time, @awcanada has made it more convenient. All you have to do is bring your cup back during your next visit and they’ll swap it out for a freshly cleaned & sanitized One Cup. This is especially great for folks like me who would “forget their head if it wasn’t attached” - Mom.

You’ll also get a 20 cent discount on each beverage that you purchase using the One Cup - which, hey - if you’re getting your morning coffee at the Brew Bar every day before work, after about 3 weeks that cup is paying YOU 🤷🏼‍♀️ #GirlMath

I’ve personally noticed how throughout the years, A&W seems to lead the way in a lot of these sustainability efforts within the quick service restaurant industry, and this seems to be no different. They are the first QSR brand to launch this type of One Cup exchangeable program, nation-wide. Go Canada! 🇨🇦

@awcanada is on a journey to reduce waste in landfills and I believe this will make it easier for customers to join them in those efforts. Let’s all give ‘em a hand 👏🤝

If you are resistant to the idea of going to couples therapy or reading books about improving your relationship because you see it as an indication that your relationship must be failing, you are doing yourself a disservice. 

One major takeaway I’ve found since diving into this stuff is that every one of us has childhood wounds - and though oftentimes it’s hard to recognize what those might be, the unresolved pain is subconsciously projected towards our partners in an effort to find healing. It’s a wild concept but is widely recognized in relationship psychology. The benefit is found if both parties can recognize what those wounds are, how they might be triggered, and how they can help their partner find that internal resolution. Knowing our own triggers will allow us to have a better understanding of our reactions and sensitivities, and understanding your partner’s triggers will give you the opportunity to give them the healing they’ve been seeking since they were just a wee child.

My therapist once told me that relationships hold a mirror to ourselves. As challenging as it might be to look, it can be a powerful tool towards self-acceptance. I’m still working on that part, but I can say for sure that nobody has brought me closer to knowing myself more than @e.s.r.j. He is calm, patient, consistent in his moods, consistent in his availability, never responds with anger, and is never reactive. It’s different from what I’ve ever known and that alone has helped to heal the anxious kid that still lives inside. The “safety” in his consistency means that I don’t have to be on the lookout for what might happen next. I’m not walking on egg shells. I can relax. And that makes it possible to recognize other parts of myself that have always been overshadowed by fears and “what ifs”.
